As Jynee Ng wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/19/2004 at 10:27:33 (Eastern Time),
>When we solving a line integral in a vector field in 3D, we can 
>parameterise the function to just one variable and solve the problem.
>For example,
>Vector F(x; y; z) = F1(x; y; z)i + F2(x; y; z)j + F3(x; y; z)k
>to get the work done for the Vector F between two points, we can 
>parameterise the Vector F and integrate separately with respect to 
>x, y and z as follow (Note that Z = Integral):
>Work Done =Z cF1(x; y; z)dx + F2(x; y; z)dy + F3(x; y; z)dz
>
>so in this way, we can solve the question by parameterization that 
>is find the x representation in a variable (let's say 't') then find 
>the y representation in 't' and also z representation in 't'. By 
>doing in this way, we can simplify our work on integration and solve 
>the problem easily. 
>
>My doubt is, can we say we are 'Parameterizing a Vector F given'?
>
>In another case, can we Parameterise a Function f(x, y, z)?
>
>Thanks in advance
>
>Regards,
>Jynee Ng

You are not parameterizing the function but rather parameterizing the
curve (or line) over which you are taking the line integral.  Does
that make sense?

